          "id": "opt-1",
          "caseNumber": 1,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Quantify low vision",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Quantify low vision",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Low vision is when a patient\u2019s visual needs exceed his or her visual capabilities. This may occur with a VA of 20/40 in one patient\nand 20/200 in another. As such, there are no set measurements that quantify low vision as in legal blindness.\nThe low vision examination consists of history, examination and a trial of variety of low vision aids. The history determines the\npatient\u2019s visual and functional goals in regards to attention to daily living, occupation, or hobbies. The examination should include\nmeasuring visual acuity with a low vision chart or by moving the patient closer to the chart. Both distance and near visual acuity\nshould be measured. Other findings that may influence the type of aid prescribed should be noted such as other physical disabilities,\nnystagmus, photophobia, aniridia, etc. An optimal refraction should be obtained using Kestenbaum\u2019s Rule to estimate the strength of a\nnear add.",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Quantify low vision"
        },
