        {
          "id": "opt-6",
          "caseNumber": 6,
          "source": "",
          "title": "What needs to be considered for IOL calculations",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "What needs to be considered for IOL calculations post-refractive surgery?",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Keratometry assumes a normal relationship between the anterior and posterior corneal curvatures and measure the anterior corneal\nradius. Incisional keratorefractive surgery for myopia flattens both the anterior and posterior corneal radius. Ablative keratorefractive\nsurgery for myopia flattens the anterior corneal radius but leaves the posterior corneal radius mostly unchanged. Standard\nkeratometry extrapolates the central corneal power based on paracentral measurements but in these settings will over-\nestimate the central corneal power leading to postoperative hyperopic surprise.\nIn addition, if the central power is very low, many formulas assume the anterior chamber is shallow and the IOL will sit closer to the\ncornea than normal and call for less power. The Holladay 2 formula and Double K correction method with SRK/T, Hoffer Q or\nHolladay 1 formulas can compensate for this error.",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "What needs to be considered for IOL calculations post-refractive surgery?"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-7",
          "caseNumber": 7,
          "source": "",
          "title": "How is accommodative amplitude measured?",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "How is accommodative amplitude measured?",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "One eye is occluded with the best distance correction in place. Slowly move a target closer to the eye while strongly encouraging the\npatient to keep it in focus. The target is slid along a Prince rule or an RAF (royal air force) rule. Record the point at which the patient\nis no longer able to keep the target in focus. Repeat for the other eye. The dioptric value of the NPA is then equal to the\naccommodative amplitude.\nFor presbyopes, test with a +3.00 add then subtract 3D from accommodative amplitude measured",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "How is accommodative amplitude measured?"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-8",
          "caseNumber": 8,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Transposing plus to minus cylinder",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Transposing plus to minus cylinder",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Transpose the following: +2.50 + 0.75 x 55\nIn order to transpose from plus to minus cylinder you must:\n1) Add the sphere and cylinder together\n(+2.50 +0.75= +3.25)\n2) Change the sign of the cylinder (+0.75 \ud83e\udc6a - 0.75)\n3) Add 90 to the axis (55 +90 = 145)\nNow put it together! +3.25 \u2013 0.75 x 145",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Transposing plus to minus cylinder"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-9",
          "caseNumber": 9,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Dealing with a patient who is not accepting spectacle",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Dealing with a patient who is not accepting spectacle correction of astigmatism?",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "- Always re-refract and ensure the patient has the correct refraction (pay attention to significant anisometropia)\n- Check if ordered glasses were correctly made (Rx, placement of optical centers, base curves of new glasses match old\nglasses, minus cylinder ground on to back of lens)\n- Minimize vertex distance to decrease magnification\n- Reassure the patient that it may take time to adjust to new prescription\n- Note if the cylinders are at oblique angles to one another\n- Decrease the power of the cylinder while keeping S.E. constant\n- Rotate the cylinder towards 90 or 180 meridian\n- Discuss CL or refractive surgery when appropriate",
              "keyPoints": [
                "Always re-refract and ensure the patient has the correct refraction (pay attention to significant anisometropia)",
                "Check if ordered glasses were correctly made (Rx, placement of optical centers, base curves of new glasses match old",
                "Minimize vertex distance to decrease magnification",
                "Reassure the patient that it may take time to adjust to new prescription",
                "Note if the cylinders are at oblique angles to one another",
                "Decrease the power of the cylinder while keeping S.E. constant",
                "Rotate the cylinder towards 90 or 180 meridian",
                "Discuss CL or refractive surgery when appropriate"
              ],
