          "title": "How do you assess the fit of an RGP lens? Soft lens?",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "How do you assess the fit of an RGP lens? Soft lens?",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Basic Evaluation\n\u25cf refract the patient, get the sphere in minus cylinder (use sphere only unless fitting toric lens)\n\u25cf correct this value for vertex distance\n\u25cf evaluate the patient\u2019s corneal health\n\u25cf obtain keratometry\nRGP LENS (better for patients with high ametropia, astigmatism, corneal irregularities / less comfortable)\n\u25cf First lens choice should have base curve 0.5D plus the flattest K reading\n\u25cf Fluorescein test\no Slight apical clearing, mid peripheral touch with slight edge clearance => Good Fit\no Apical touch with peripheral => too loose\n\u25aa choose a steeper base curve (smaller radius of curvature) or larger lens diameter\no Apical clearance with central pooling, bubbles => too tight\n\u25aa choose a flatter base curve (larger radius of curvature) or smaller lens diameter\n\u25cf Remember SAM/FAP rule if you change base curve\no Steeper add Minus to power\no Flatter add Plus to power\nSOFT LENS\n\u25aa Movement on Blink: CTL should move 1mm down with blink and reposition\no too much movement, it is too loose (flat)\no too little, too tight (steep)\n\u25aa Centration: should cover entire cornea\n\u25aa Sag: lens should drop 0.5 to 1 mm on upgaze\n\u25aa Toric: check lens rotation and stability",
              "keyPoints": [
                "refract the patient, get the sphere in minus cylinder (use sphere only unless fitting toric lens)",
                "correct this value for vertex distance",
                "evaluate the patient\u2019s corneal health",
                "obtain keratometry",
                "First lens choice should have base curve 0.5D plus the flattest K reading",
