        {
          "id": "opt-13",
          "caseNumber": 13,
          "source": "",
          "title": "What is chromatic aberration & duochrome test?",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "What is chromatic aberration & duochrome test?",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Chromatic aberration\nWhen polychromatic light passes through a lens, shorter wavelengths (blue) are refracted (bent) more than longer wavelengths\n(red) so that the former comes in focus closer to the lens than the latter. This is caused by the prismatic effect of lenses.\nDuochrome test\nThis principle is applied in the duochrome test used to refine the spherical endpoint after performing manifest refraction. It is a\nmonocular test (done with each eye separately). First, the eye is fogged by adding +0.5 D to relax accommodation. A chart is shown\nwith black letters on a half-red and half-green background. The letters on the red side should be in sharper focus first due to fogging.\nThen, minus sphere is dialed in until the letters are equally clear on the red and green sides.\n\u201cRAM GAP\u201d - Red add minus, green add plus\nThere is a 1.0 D difference between the red and green light-rays. The duochrome test results in the image being in best focus on the\nretina for white light conditions.\nDoes this test work on color blind individuals?\nYes, because it relies on chromatic aberration, not on color discrimination.\nWhat range of VA is required to perform the duochrome test?\n20/30 or better",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "What is chromatic aberration & duochrome test?"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-14",
          "caseNumber": 14,
          "source": "",
          "title": "What is a Geneva lens clock?",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "What is a Geneva lens clock?",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Measures the radius of curvature of a lens surface by the deflection of a movable pin. Base curves affect the magnification of the lens\nindependent of the lens power. If a patient is accustomed to a certain base curve (magnification), a change in base curve - with\nconstant overall dioptric power \u2013 may cause asthenopic symptoms.",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "What is a Geneva lens clock?"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-15",
          "caseNumber": 15,
          "source": "",
          "title": "What is a lensmeter?",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "What is a lens meter?",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "A lens meter is used to measure sphere, cylinder, axis, prism and locate the optical center of a lens\nIt works based on the optometer principle and is made of an illuminated movable target behind a fixed lens, and a place between the\nfixed lens and telescope to position the unknown lens. The target is moved to determine the focal length and thus the power of the\nunknown lens.\nHow to use the instrument:\n1. Rotate the axis dial until the narrow lines are all parallel\n2. Rotate the drum until the narrow lines are in focus. This is sphere\n3. Rotate the drum until the solid lines are in focus. Should be in positive direction otherwise rotate axis 90 degrees.\nFor prism: Make sure lens is centered and location of center of target from center cross hairs is noted. Each concentric circle away\nfrom center equals 1 PD. Nasal= Base-in, Temporal= Base-out, Superior = Base up, Inferior = Base down",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "What is a lensmeter?"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-16",
          "caseNumber": 16,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Unhappy patient with current glasses: what do you do?",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Unhappy patient with current glasses: what do you do?",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Take a detailed history to find out:\n\u25cf Symptoms: blurred vision, distorted vision, anisokonia, asthenopia, diploplia\n\u25cf Setting: Difficulty with distance reading? near reading? Bifocal segment? Night-time? Glare?\n\u25cf Old Mrx better: have patient bring in old glasses to compare\nEvaluation\n\u25cf Correct Mrx \u2013 repeat refraction, cycloplegic if concern for over-minused\n\u25cf Correct glasses: Does not match Mrx, astigmatism axis wrong/power too strong\n\u25cf Amount and axis of cylinder \u2013 rotate closer to 90 or 180 degrees\n\u25cf Mechanical\no Check fit\no Check optical centers (unintentional prism)\no Check vertex distance (may be different from old glasses)\no Check base curve using lens clock (if different then previous lenses can change magnification)\n\u25cf Bifocals: style of add changed, segment placement, progressive Rx not strong enough requiring patient to look too low,\n\u25cf Induced prism from anisometropia \u2013 slab off prism, CL, lower both optical centers, single vision glasses, dissimilar segments,\nFresnel prism over bifocal segment\n\u25cf Night vision issues: Pt may over accommodate at night due to no target and induce myopia. Add -0.25D\n\u25cf Ocular pathology: surgically induced anisometropia(Usually < 2 D), ocular surface, cataract, retina finding\n\u25cf Check for phoria or tropia",
              "keyPoints": [
                "Symptoms: blurred vision, distorted vision, anisokonia, asthenopia, diploplia",
                "Setting: Difficulty with distance reading? near reading? Bifocal segment? Night-time? Glare?",
                "Old Mrx better: have patient bring in old glasses to compare",
                "Correct Mrx \u2013 repeat refraction, cycloplegic if concern for over-minused",
                "Correct glasses: Does not match Mrx, astigmatism axis wrong/power too strong",
                "Amount and axis of cylinder \u2013 rotate closer to 90 or 180 degrees",
                "Mechanical",
                "Bifocals: style of add changed, segment placement, progressive Rx not strong enough requiring patient to look too low,",
                "Induced prism from anisometropia \u2013 slab off prism, CL, lower both optical centers, single vision glasses, dissimilar segments,",
                "Night vision issues: Pt may over accommodate at night due to no target and induce myopia. Add -0.25D",
                "Ocular pathology: surgically induced anisometropia(Usually < 2 D), ocular surface, cataract, retina finding",
                "Check for phoria or tropia"
              ],
              "scoringKeywords": [
                "Symptoms",
                "Mechanical",
                "Induced prism from anisometropia",
                "Setting",
                "Old Mrx better",
                "Ocular pathology",
                "Night vision issues",
                "Correct Mrx",
                "Bifocals",
                "Amount and axis of cylinder",
                "Check for phoria or tropia",
                "Correct glasses"
              ]
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Unhappy patient with current glasses: what do you do?"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-17",
          "caseNumber": 17,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Explain Spherical aberration",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Explain Spherical aberration",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Rays that strike the periphery of a lens system will be more strongly bent (if positive spherical aberration is present), effectively\nshortening its focal length. This becomes a problem with widely dilated pupils (pharmacologic or in low light levels) causing the\npatient to become more myopic,\nThis explains the phenomenon in retinoscopy when you have against movement in periphery and with movement centrally. Peripheral\nlens refracts light more strongly than central rays so periphery appears more myopic. One should neutralize central reflex.",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Explain Spherical aberration"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-18",
          "caseNumber": 18,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Explain critical angle",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Explain critical angle, total internal reflection and its application to ophthalmology",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "CRITICAL ANGLE is the angle at which light is bent exactly 90 degress away from the normal causing light to run parallel with the\nrefractive interface. When the angle of incidence exceeds the critical angle the light is reflected back into the material with the higher\nindex of refraction causing TOTAL INTERNAL REFRACTION. Light leaving the angle (i.e trabecular meshwork) is reflected back\ninto the anterior chamber at the tear-air interface bacause of total internal reflection. Gonioscopy overcomes this by eliminating the\ntear-air interface.",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Explain critical angle, total internal reflection and its application to ophthalmology"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-19",
          "caseNumber": 19,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Explain the prismatic effect of glasses on strabismic",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Explain the prismatic effect of glasses on strabismic deviations",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Plus lenses decrease the measured deviation, whether ET, XT or HT\nMinus Lenses increase the measured deviation, whether ET, XT or HT\nThe true deviation is changed by approximately (2.5) (D) % where D = bilateral spectacle lens power\nFor example an exotrope of 40 prism D wearing -10.00 sphere glasses will measure:\n(2.5) (10) = 25% more XT for a total of 50 prism D of XT\n3M mnemonic: Minus Measures More",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Explain the prismatic effect of glasses on strabismic deviations"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-20",
          "caseNumber": 20,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Bifocal Segments- prismatic effects (image jump vs.",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Bifocal Segments- prismatic effects (image jump vs. image displacement)",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Image jump \u2013 due to sudden introduction of prismatic power at top of bifocal segment. With round top segments, sudden introduction\nof base down prism causes an object to \u201cjump\u201d upward as the eye moves down. If optical center of bifocal is at top of segment (as in\nFranklin or Executive type) or progressives, there is no image jump.\nImage displacement \u2013 produced by total prismatic power acting in the reading position. Minimized when prismatic effect of bifocal is\nopposite to that of the distance segment.\nMyopic patients should be given flat top segments (Franklin/Executive style). This minimizes both image jump and image\ndisplacement.\nHyperopic patients \u2013 round tops minimize image displacement and maximize image jump; flat top or Franklin-type segments\nminimize image jump while maximizing image displacement.\nImage jump is more bothersome than image displacement. In practice, many opticians give flat top segments to myopes and hyperopes\nbecause flat top segments are easier and cheaper to assemble. As long as a patient is not complaining, this is acceptable.",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Bifocal Segments- prismatic effects (image jump vs. image displacement)"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-21",
          "caseNumber": 21,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Patient complains that glasses fog and get dirty.",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Patient complains that glasses fog and get dirty",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Tight Frames (poor air circulation): adjust tilt to minimize contact and increase vertex distance.\nLarge frames (rub the eyebrows or rest on the cheeks): change to a smaller frame size.\nGlass frames: change to plastic lenses which conduct heat more poorly than glass.\nTreat underlying eye conditions:\n- epiphora may cause fogging\n- seborrheic dermatitis may promote deposition of dirt and oil on the lenses.",
              "keyPoints": [
                "epiphora may cause fogging",
                "seborrheic dermatitis may promote deposition of dirt and oil on the lenses."
              ],
              "scoringKeywords": [
                "seborrheic dermatitis may promote deposition of dirt and oil on the lenses.",
                "epiphora may cause fogging"
              ]
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Patient complains that glasses fog and get dirty."
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-22",
          "caseNumber": 22,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Why would hyperopic patient slide glasses down his/her",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Why would hyperopic patient slide glasses down his/her nose?",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Moving a lens, either plus or minus, away from the eye gives it more effective plus power since it pulls its far point with it. For\ndistance viewing this would help the patient if the plus lens prescribed is too weak. The patient can slide his glasses forward to adjust\nfor this error. Another reason is that near viewing can be enhanced by increasing the effective plus power.",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Why would hyperopic patient slide glasses down his/her nose?"
        },
        {
          "id": "opt-23",
          "caseNumber": 23,
          "source": "",
          "title": "Describe the technique of streak retinoscopy.",
          "subspecialty": "Optics",
          "presentation": "Describe the technique of streak retinoscopy",
          "imageFile": null,
          "imageFiles": [],
          "photoDescription": "",
          "questions": [
            {
              "number": 1,
              "question": "Discussion",
              "answer": "Retinoscopy is a method of objectively measuring the refractive state of an eye. With a phoropter or free lenses, the examiner moves\nthe light streak across the pupil and changes the correcting lens until the reflex movement is neutralized (pupil appears uniformly\nilluminated). The final refraction is determined by adjusting for working distance.\nMyopic: far point between examiner and pupil => reflex moves in direction opposite to retinoscope sweep.\nHyperopic: far point behind examiner => reflex moves in same direction as retinoscope sweep.",
              "keyPoints": [],
              "scoringKeywords": []
            }
          ],
          "diagnosisTitle": "Describe the technique of streak retinoscopy."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}